         <entryFree xml:id="k000103" type="architectural feature">
            <term xml:id="term-k000103-8" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt" type="preferred">ang</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000103-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">昂</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000103-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">昂</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000103-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">áng</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000103-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile">ang</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000103-6" xml:lang="en" type="literal_translation" source="#biblk000103-3">raise up; lift up (lit.)</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000103-1" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000103-1" type="ATTCAT preferred">slanted bracket arms (ATTCAT preferred)</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000103-7" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000103-2">(descending or ascending) cantilevers</term>
            <note type="Note (brief)">
               <p xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000103-5">"Ang" literally means "high" or "lifting" and it was originally interchangeable with 仰 (yang).</p>
               <p xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000103-6">As a term used in traditional Chinese architecture, ang refers to an angled timber member used in corbel bracket sets and placed perpendicular to the building plane.</p>
               <p xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000103-7">There are five other terms used to refer to this same timber element: ang 㰇, feiang飛昂 (lit. flying ang), ying'ang英昂 (lit. heroic ang), xiejiao斜角 (lit. oblique angle), and xiaang下昂(lit. descending ang). In historical literature, feiang is used more often than other names. According to the Yingzao fashi (1103), there are two primary kinds of ang: xiaang and <term ref="/keyword/k000137">shang'ang </term>. When a xiaang are used in a corner corbel bracket sets轉角斗栱, they are called jiaoang 角昂 and youang由昂. The Yingzao fashi also includes a special kind of ang: the chaang 插昂 (lit. inserted ang).</p>
               <p xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000103-8">There are also <term ref="/keyword/k000172">huagong 華栱</term> (lit. blossoming bracket-arms) whose "elbows" are carved to look like an ang on the exterior-side of the building in early extant structures, such as the Sage Mother Hall in Jinci from the Northern Song dynasty. These are called "pretend ang" (jiaang 假昂) by architectural historians. This kind of timber member becomes standard in the <term ref="/keyword/k000051">Ming</term> and <term ref="/keyword/k000070">Qing</term> dynasties. The ang that are used in buildings and mentioned in architectural literature from the Qing dynasty are just this kind of element.</p>
               <p xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000103-9">During the <term ref="/keyword/k000074">Song</term> and <term ref="/keyword/k000036">Jin</term> dynasties (10th-13th centuries) it was popular to make shuatou look like xiaang. These are called slanted bracket arm-shaped shuatou  (<term ref="/keyword/k000001">angxing shuatou 昂形耍頭</term>).</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">“昂”字的本意為高或抬起，與“仰”字通假（漢語大詞典）。作為中國古代建築術語，“昂”為组织在斗栱中的一類垂直于屋身，用于出挑的斜向構件（國 2002，16; 陳,2010，190)。也稱為㰇、飛昂、英昂、斜角或下昂。但在歷史文獻中“飛昂”相對多見。《營造法式》(1103)中昂的種類包括“下昂”與“<term ref="/keyword/k000137">上昂 shang'ang</term>”，用於轉角斗栱中的下昂稱為“角昂”和“由昂”。此外，较为特殊的還有“插昂”。（YZFS，4.4b-4.7a）</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">在现存建筑实例中，宋以后出现向外一端做成昂嘴形状的平置华栱，被建筑史学者称为假昂。此类做法在<term ref="/keyword/k000051">明</term><term ref="/keyword/k000070">清</term> (17-20世纪)成为定制。清代建筑及建筑文献中的昂均指此类构件（梁 1981,21-22）。<term ref="/keyword/k000074">宋</term><term ref="/keyword/k000036">金</term>时期 (10-13世纪)也曾广泛流行将斗栱中的耍头作成下昂形式的做法，被建筑史学者称为<term ref="/keyword/k000001">angxing shuatou 昂形耍頭</term>（喻，2017）。</p>
            </note>
